{
  "texts": [
    "The only way we could model the LLM's measurement error in approximating that quantity would be to collect enough human subject responses to calculate the target quantity V r on that very design.",
    "But then why use the LLM at all?",
    "As a consequence, LLMs as human subject simulators are likely to only add value to experimental studies where the research context contains a large number of designs, r. In that setting, collecting human subject responses V r on a small subset of designs r allows us to model the LLM's error ∆ r and correct the LLM outputs on the remaining designs.",
    "For example, we could collect LLM responses on all menus in the Choices13K dataset and only collect human subject responses on a small validation sample, drastically reducing the cost of data collection.",
    "Once again, in-silico subjects can only serve to amplify, rather than fully replace, human subjects in such experimental studies."
  ]
}